disability.

Friedman SL(1), Helm DT, Woodman AC.

Author information:
(1)University of Colorado, CO, USA. sandra.friedman@childrenscolorado.org

As life expectancy of people with intellectual disability (ID) has increased, 
there has been a concurrent increase in age-related illnesses and conditions 
similar to that of the general population. These circumstances result in people 
with ID dying from typical life-ending conditions, and thus, they require 
similar end-of-life services such as palliative and hospice care. Although there 
are notable barriers to hospice for all, people with ID face additional 
challenges in accessing the benefits of these services. This article presents a 
review of the literature on these issues, underscoring the multiple challenges 
and the importance of a more collaborative approach between hospice and 
palliative care workers with people with ID, their families, and other important 
stakeholders.

